<p>Evaluate each of the following limits. Show sufficient work to justify each answer. For infinite limits, you must clearly show whether the limit is $\infty$ or $-\infty$. </p>

<p>
$
\lim_{x\to 3}\frac{\sqrt{x^2 + 7}-4}{x-3} = ?
$
</p>


<pl-image-capture file-name="3a.jpg"></pl-image-capture> 

<p><b>Solution:</b></p>

<p>Direct substitution gives  
$\displaystyle\frac{\sqrt{3^2+7}-4}{3-3}=\frac{4-4}{0}=\frac{0}{0}$,  
an indeterminate form.</p>

<p>Multiply numerator and denominator by the conjugate $\sqrt{x^2+7}+4$:</p>
<p>$$
\frac{\sqrt{x^2+7}-4}{x-3}\;\cdot\;\frac{\sqrt{x^2+7}+4}{\sqrt{x^2+7}+4}
=\frac{x^2+7-16}{(x-3)\bigl(\sqrt{x^2+7}+4\bigr)}
=\frac{x^2-9}{(x-3)\bigl(\sqrt{x^2+7}+4\bigr)}.
$$</p>

<p>Factor $x^2-9=(x-3)(x+3)$ and cancel $(x-3)$:</p>
<p>$$
\frac{(x-3)(x+3)}{(x-3)\bigl(\sqrt{x^2+7}+4\bigr)}
=\frac{x+3}{\sqrt{x^2+7}+4},\quad x\neq3.
$$</p>

<p>Now take the limit as $x\to3$:</p>
<p>$$
\lim_{x\to3}\frac{x+3}{\sqrt{x^2+7}+4}
=\frac{3+3}{\sqrt{9+7}+4}
=\frac{6}{4+4}
=\frac{6}{8}
=\frac{3}{4}.
$$</p>

<p>Therefore,  
$$\lim_{x\to3}\frac{\sqrt{x^2+7}-4}{x-3}=\frac{3}{4}\,. $$
</p>

